        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Leads Overview",
            Slug = "leads-overview",
            Summary = "What leads are, how the sales pipeline works, lead statuses, converting leads to customers, and how leads connect to quotes and jobs.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","sales"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Leads Overview\n\nThe Leads module is your sales pipeline. It tracks potential customers from first contact through qualification and quoting to conversion or loss. Every lead represents a company that might become a customer — and every customer relationship starts here.\n\n### What Is a Lead?\n\nA lead is a prospective customer record. It captures the company name, contact person, email, phone, how they found you (source), and any notes about the opportunity. Leads move through a defined pipeline of statuses as you work them.\n\n### The Sales Pipeline\n\nLeads progress through five statuses:\n\n1. **New** — A fresh lead that hasn't been contacted yet. This is the default status when you create a lead.\n2. **Contacted** — You've reached out to the prospect. They know who you are and what you offer.\n3. **Quoting** — The prospect has expressed interest and you're preparing or have sent a quote/estimate.\n4. **Converted** — The lead became a customer. A Customer record is created automatically when you convert.\n5. **Lost** — The opportunity didn't work out. You can record a reason (competitor won, budget, timing, etc.) for future analysis.\n\nLeads can move forward or backward through New, Contacted, and Quoting freely. Converted and Lost are terminal states, though a Lost lead can be reopened back to New.\n\n### Two Ways to View Your Pipeline\n\nThe Leads page offers two view modes:\n\n- **Table View** — A sortable, filterable list showing all leads with columns for company, contact, source, status, follow-up date, and created date. Best for searching and bulk review.\n- **Pipeline View** — A board with a column for each status. Drag and drop cards between columns to update status. Best for visual pipeline management.\n\nSwitch between views using the buttons in the page header. Your preference is saved.\n\n### Follow-Up Dates\n\nEach lead can have a follow-up date. When the follow-up date passes without the lead being updated, the date displays in red (overdue) as a visual reminder. Use follow-up dates to ensure no lead falls through the cracks.\n\n### Lead Sources\n\nThe Source field tracks how leads find you — referral, website, trade show, cold call, etc. Your admin sets the list of sources, so your team can add new ones anytime. Tracking sources helps you understand which marketing channels produce results.\n\n### Converting Leads to Customers\n\nWhen a lead is ready to become a customer, click the single **Convert to Customer** button in the lead panel. It's one click — it creates the customer from the lead's company name, contact, email, and phone, changes the lead status to Converted, and takes you straight to the new customer's page. There's no multi-step panel and no separate 'Convert + Create Job' button; the credit, tax, and address details are filled in afterward on the customer page.\n\nConversion does not create a Job. Jobs are produced later from the customer's quotes and Sales Orders (see the flow below). Conversion is a one-way action. Once converted, the lead shows a green confirmation badge and links to the customer record. You cannot convert a Lost lead — reopen it first.\n\n### How Leads Connect to Quotes and Jobs\n\nThe typical flow is: Lead → Customer → Quote/Estimate → Sales Order → Job. Converting a lead creates the Customer record. From there, you can create Estimates (ballpark figures) or Quotes (binding, line-itemized) for that customer. When a quote is accepted, it converts to a Sales Order, which can generate Jobs on the board.\n\n### Marking a Lead as Lost\n\nWhen you mark a lead as Lost (either by clicking the Lost status button or dragging the card to the Lost column in pipeline view), a panel appears asking for the reason. The lost reason is required — you can't confirm without entering one. It's valuable too: it helps you identify patterns (price too high, competitor won, bad timing) and improve your win rate over time.\n\n### Reopening Lost Leads\n\nCircumstances change. A Lost lead can be reopened by clicking the 'Reopen Lead' button in the detail view. This resets the status to New so you can work the opportunity again.","sections":[]}"""
        });

