        // ── Suppression / Do-Not-Contact (Article) ───────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Suppression & Do-Not-Contact",
            Slug = "leads-suppression",
            Summary = "The per-channel opt-out and cooldown list: how leads get suppressed, what the channels mean, and how to lift a suppression or clear a cooldown.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 11,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads/suppression"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","suppression","compliance","dnc"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Suppression & Do-Not-Contact\n\nThe Suppression / Do-Not-Contact page (Leads → Suppression) is where opt-outs and cooldown windows live. It exists so you don't re-contact someone who asked you not to, and so re-contact timing respects the cooldown rules. New opt-outs and cooldowns accumulate here as they're recorded across the system.\n\n### Per-Channel Suppression\n\nSuppression is **per channel**, not all-or-nothing. A lead can opt out of one channel while staying reachable on another:\n\n- **Email opt-out** — don't email this lead.\n- **Call opt-out** — don't call this lead.\n- **SMS opt-out** — don't text this lead.\n\nThe Suppression column on each row shows a red label for every channel the lead has opted out of. A lead might show an email opt-out but still be callable, for example.\n\n### Cooldowns\n\nSeparate from a hard opt-out is a **cooldown** — a temporary \"don't contact until\" window. A lead in cooldown shows a warning label with the wait-until date and an optional reason. Cooldowns come from outreach policy (for instance, a campaign's default cooldown override) and the queue/intake logic respects them: a lead still in cooldown is held back from the call queue and skipped during bulk import.\n\n### How Leads Land Here\n\nLeads reach the suppression list a few ways:\n\n- A rep hits **Suppress** on a lead while working the call queue, because the prospect asked not to be contacted.\n- An inbound opt-out (an unsubscribe or a do-not-call request) turns off the matching channel.\n- An outreach policy or campaign sets a cooldown window.\n\n### Reviewing the List\n\nThe table shows the company, contact, email, phone, the suppression labels, the wait-until date, the cooldown reason, and when the preferences were last updated. Clicking a row opens that lead so you can see the full picture.\n\n### Lifting a Suppression\n\nWhen an opt-out was a mistake or the prospect has re-engaged, you can re-enable outreach **one channel at a time** from the row's action buttons:\n\n- **Lift email opt-out** (mail icon) — re-enables email.\n- **Lift call opt-out** (phone icon) — re-enables calling.\n- **Lift SMS opt-out** (sms icon) — re-enables texting.\n\nEach button only appears when that channel is actually suppressed. Lifting one channel leaves the others untouched. The change is recorded in the lead's activity log so there's an audit trail of who re-enabled what.\n\n### Clearing a Cooldown\n\nIf a lead is in a cooldown window you want to end early, the **Clear cooldown** button (schedule icon) removes the cooldown-until date so the lead becomes contactable again immediately. This is independent of the channel opt-outs — clearing a cooldown doesn't touch any opt-out flags.","sections":[]}"""
        });

