        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Lead Qualification & Classification",
            Slug = "leads-qualification",
            Summary = "Using the classification chips (capability fit, NDA, ITAR/export-control) and reading the engagement-signal strip (playbook hint, recent comms, stale flag) on the lead detail panel.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 12,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","qualification","classification","itar","nda"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Lead Qualification & Classification\n\nOpen any lead's panel and below the basic info you'll find two qualification strips: a **classification strip** for tagging the lead's manufacturing and compliance fit, and an **engagement-signal strip** that tells you, at a glance, what to do next. Together they turn a raw contact into a qualified, prioritized opportunity.\n\n### Classification Labels\n\nThe classification strip carries up to four colored labels. The campaign label is read-only; the other three are click-to-set — click the label, pick a value from the menu, and it saves right away.\n\n**Capability fit** — can your shop actually make what this prospect needs?\n- *Not assessed* — the starting value, nobody has judged it yet.\n- *Fits* — squarely in your wheelhouse.\n- *Needs review* — an engineer should look before you commit.\n- *Doesn't fit* — outside your capabilities; qualify out early rather than waste a quote.\n\n**NDA** — where the non-disclosure agreement stands:\n- *None*, *Requested*, *In force*, *Expired*. Track this so you don't share sensitive specs before an NDA is in force, and so you notice when one lapses.\n\n**ITAR / export control** — export-control clearance for defense or controlled work:\n- *N/A*, *Pending*, *Cleared*, *Denied*. For ITAR-controlled work this matters before any technical data changes hands.\n\n**Campaign** (read-only) — if the lead came from a bulk-marketing campaign, this label names it and links to the Campaigns page. It's set at intake and isn't reassigned from the lead.\n\nEach label is color-coded, so a row of green labels reads very differently from a row with a red \"Doesn't fit\" or \"Denied\". Setting a label is one click and is recorded in the lead's activity history.\n\n### The Engagement-Signal Strip\n\nNear the top of the detail body, an engagement strip gives working guidance. It's shown only while the lead is active (hidden once the lead is Converted or Lost, since the guidance no longer applies):\n\n- **Playbook hint** — driven by the lead's engagement shape (Quick quote, Strategic, Prototype, etc.). It reminds you what this kind of deal needs next — e.g., a strategic account's hint nudges you toward mapping the decision-maker and champion.\n- **Recent-engagement label** — shows a count of recent communications (\"3 recent comms\"), so you know whether the lead has been actively worked or has gone quiet.\n- **Stale badge** — appears when there's been **no activity in the last 14 days**. It's a prompt to follow up or reclassify before the opportunity goes cold.\n\n### Why This Matters\n\nThe classification chips and engagement signals are how a lead earns its place in the work queue. A lead that fits your capabilities, has its NDA in force, is export-clearable, and shows recent engagement is a strong opportunity worth your time. One that doesn't fit, or has gone stale for weeks, is a candidate to qualify out or re-prioritize. Keeping these tags current means the team spends effort where it pays off — and the compliance flags (NDA, ITAR) keep you from sharing controlled information before you're cleared to.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Leads — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "leads-reference",
            Summary = "Deeper how-to for experienced reps: reading the bulk-import duplicate labels, the call-queue keyboard cheat sheet, how a suppression or wait period lifts, when a sample goes stale on its own, why an account won't delete, and how engagement-shape fields carry.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/leads"]""",
            Tags = """["leads","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Leads — Advanced Reference\n\nThe deeper how-to for reps who work leads all day. For everyday basics see the Overview, Walkthrough, and Field Reference modules; this page covers the tips, gotchas, and edge cases you hit once you're moving real volume.\n\n## Getting a Messy Spreadsheet to Import Cleanly\n\nWhen you bulk-import leads, you don't have to reformat your spreadsheet first. The import reads your column headings loosely — capitalization doesn't matter, and common wordings all work. \"Company\", \"Company Name\", and \"companyname\" are all read as the company. \"Email\" and \"email address\" both work; so do \"Phone\", \"phone number\", and \"tel\". The only column that has to be there is the company name; contact, email, phone, source, and notes are all optional. Any heading it doesn't recognize is simply left out — so an extra column you don't need won't break the import.\n\nBefore anything is added, the import previews every row and labels it so you can see at a glance what will happen. The labels tell you why a row will or won't be brought in:\n\n- **Will create** — the row is good and gets added when you commit.\n- **Missing required field** — the field your outreach type needs is blank. A cold-call batch needs a phone; a cold-email batch needs an email.\n- **Missing company** — no company name, the one thing every lead has to have.\n- **Duplicate in batch** — the same email or phone shows up earlier in the same file, so you're not importing it twice.\n- **Duplicate lead** — the email or phone already matches a lead you have. (Email matching ignores upper/lower case; phone matches on the digits, so formatting differences don't fool it.)\n- **Already a customer** — the email or phone belongs to a contact on a customer you already sell to.\n- **Opted out** — this person asked not to be contacted on the channel your batch uses.\n- **In wait period** — this person is still inside a don't-contact-until window.\n\nCommitting brings in only the \"will create\" rows and skips the rest for you. Each new lead gets a note on its activity history showing it came in through a bulk import, so later you know how it arrived.\n\n## Call-Queue Keyboard Cheat Sheet\n\nThe call queue (Leads → Queue) is built to work without the mouse. Letter keys record an outcome; J and K move between leads. Shortcuts are ignored while you're typing in the notes box, so your typing is never caught.\n\n| Key | Outcome | Effect |\n|---|---|---|\n| E | Engaged | Leaves the queue and moves the lead to Contacted. |\n| N | No answer | Comes back around for a later try. |\n| V | Voicemail left | Comes back around for a later try. |\n| C | Schedule callback | Opens the callback panel; saves once you confirm. |\n| B | Bad data | Marks the lead lost (wrong number or bounce). |\n| S | Suppress | Adds the lead to the do-not-contact list. |\n| J | (move) | Go to the next lead in your batch. |\n| K | (move) | Go back to the previous lead. |\n\nEach outcome is one step and moves you on automatically. Batches don't overlap between reps, so two reps never land on the same lead.\n\n## How a Suppression or Wait Period Lifts\n\nEach channel — email, call, and text — is handled on its own, so you can suppress or re-enable one without touching the others:\n\n- Marking an email, call, or text opt-out also records when it happened and where it came from; lifting it clears both. Each change is noted in the lead's activity history.\n- A **cooldown** is a separate wait window that applies no matter the channel. Setting or clearing the wait-until date is noted too, along with its reason and any notes.\n\nThe full loop plays out like this: you suppress a channel while working the queue (or a campaign policy sets a cooldown). That holds the lead back from the call queue and from bulk import while the wait period is still active — so nobody re-dials someone who asked you to stop. Later, from the Suppression page, you lift it one channel at a time or clear the cooldown. Each lift or clear is its own step, saved on that lead and written to its activity history, so there's a clear record of who re-enabled what and when.\n\n## When a Sample Goes Stale on Its Own\n\nYou don't have to police every sample yourself. A sample moves from **Delivered** to **Stale** for you once it was delivered more than 14 days ago and still has no follow-up — no quote written from it and no loss recorded. The change shows on the sample's lead so you can see it went cold. The 14-day window gives the prospect time to evaluate without letting a sample quietly slip; your admin can adjust it. You can still mark a sample stale by hand from its outcome menu — this just catches the ones you didn't get back to.\n\n## Why an Account Won't Delete\n\nYou can't delete a B2B account while any lead still points at it — you'll get a message saying how many leads are linked and asking you to unassign the account on each one first. This keeps the link intact for history. Unassign the account on those leads (or let them convert or be lost), then try again. Converted leads no longer count.\n\n## How Engagement-Shape Fields Carry\n\nA lead remembers which New-Lead shape created it — Quick add, Quick quote, Repeat, Strategic, or Prototype (Quick add is the default). The shape-specific extras you filled in (parts and quantities, target price, needed-by date, decision-maker, champion, current vendor, project type, timeline) stay with the lead; fields you left blank simply aren't kept. Your admin can add new shapes over time as your sales motions change. When you create the lead, its shape is noted in the activity history, and the lead panel uses that shape to show you the playbook hint for that kind of deal.","sections":[]}"""
        });

